[Lumpy skin disease has spread, very recently, to Bulgaria's western neighbor -- the Former Yugoslav Republic (FYR) of Macedonia. This has already been reported to the OIE (20160423.4177438). International trade restrictions in such cases are not surprising. However, when dealing with a vectorborne disease, animal movement restrictions, while justified (and prescribed in detail by internationally agreed conventions and protocols), even if strictly abided to, are only partially sufficient to control/prevent the disease. Windborne vectors recognize no political borders.

A resembling situation was encountered when BTV-8 [bluetongue virus serotype 8] spread in northern and later central Europe, several years ago, requiring the wide application of an (inactivated!) vaccine in some countries, followed by some adjustments in the international trade requirements.

ProMED-mail has published requests for information on the ongoing research project addressing inactivated lumpy skin disease vaccines. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4179271,81.]
